<biogHist>
<abstract>Child abuse refers to behaviours of others, (usually adults) against children. The behaviours include: maltreatment, physical and psychological abuse and neglect, sexual abuse and witnessing family violence.</abstract>
<p>In 2010, a National Child Protection Clearinghouse research paper defined the types of child abuse that children needed to be protected from in Australia.<br />
• Maltreatment (Note that in practice the terms child abuse and child neglect are used more frequently than the term child maltreatment)<br />
• Physically abusive behaviour<br />
• Sexually abusive behaviour<br />
• Neglectful behaviour<br />
• Psychologically abusive or neglectful behaviour.</p>
<p>Detailed descriptions of each type of child abuse are available in the publication 'Australian legal definitions: when is a child in need of protection?'<br />
Sexual abuse of children is never the child's fault. The Children and Community Services Act 2004 (Division 9A, s.124A) makes this quite clear in the way it defines sexual abuse in relation to a child. It includes sexual behaviour in circumstances where:<br />
o the child is the subject of bribery, coercion, a threat, exploitation or violence; or<br />
o the child has less power than another person involved in the behaviour; or<br />
o there is a significant disparity in the developmental function or maturity of the child and another person involved in the behaviour.</p>

</biogHist>
